If 
\begin_inset Formula $f-g=h\in\mathbf{I}(V)$
\end_inset

, then for any point 
\begin_inset Formula $p=(a_{1},\dots,a_{m})\in V$
\end_inset

, we have 
\begin_inset Formula $f(p)-g(p)=h(p)=0$
\end_inset

.
 Hence, 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $g$
\end_inset

 represent the same function on 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

.
 Conversely, if 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $g$
\end_inset

 represent the same function, then, at every 
\begin_inset Formula $p\in V$
\end_inset

, we have 
\begin_inset Formula $f(p)-g(p)=0$
\end_inset

.
 Thus, 
\begin_inset Formula $f-g\in\mathbf{I}(V)$
\end_inset

 by definition.
